{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/malaria/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"498a864c-c278-5bde-b72a-027b19ecbc6e","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 19f85b68-1cb0-4137-826d-50b5878d1efb --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field 19f85b68-1cb0-4137-826d-50b5878d1efb -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 888b01af-4397-45c1-b74e-c173ab3d233a --><!-- begin field a66aa4fa-4201-48e0-aea1-2e7196733fe7 --><ul><li>Malaria is a life-threatening illness caused by infection of red blood cells by <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/background-information/causes/\">Plasmodium parasites</a>.</li><li>Several species of Plasmodium (<em>P. vivax</em>, <em>P. falciparum</em>, <em>P. ovale</em>, and <em>P. malariae</em>) cause malaria in humans. Human infection with <em>P. knowlesi</em>, a malaria parasite of monkeys in South-East-Asia, can also occur.</li><li>Transmission of malaria to humans occurs through the bite of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes.</li><li>The infecting agent (sporozoite) is inoculated into humans in the saliva of infected mosquitoes during a blood meal.</li><li>The sporozoites travel in the bloodstream to the liver where they enter liver cells and mature into schizonts which eventually rupture and release tens of thousands of merozoites.</li><li>Each merozoite can infect a red blood cell where they mature and divide to form more parasites. These are released into the bloodstream when the red blood cell ruptures and go on to infect other red blood cells. The number of parasites in the blood increases rapidly and produces clinical illness.</li><li>Some parasites in the red blood cells form male and female gametocytes. These mate if taken up by a mosquito and mature to release sporozoites ready to be inoculated into a new human host.</li><li>Anopheles mosquitoes are found mainly in tropical and subtropical areas of the world — malaria does not occur naturally in the UK.<ul><li>Malaria can be imported to the UK by people who have become infected during time spent in areas where malaria is endemic.</li><li>Travellers (in particular children) visiting friends and relatives are more likely than tourists to become infected with malaria as they tend to visit remote places, stay longer and are less likely to take malaria chemoprophylaxis. </li><li>UK surveillance data from 2015 showed that where history of chemoprophylaxis was known 85% (n = 490) of people who had acquired malaria while travelling abroad had not taken antimalarial medication.</li></ul></li><li>Malaria can also occur (rarely) in the UK as a result of:</li><li>\"Airport malaria\" or \"baggage malaria\" — malaria imported to non-endemic areas by infected <em>Anopheles</em> mosquitoes hiding in planes or in baggage.</li><li>Person-to-person transmission during:<ul><li>Blood transfusion or implantation of infected tissues.</li><li>Pregnancy.</li><li>Injecting drug use.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">PHE, 2011</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">ESCMID, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">Kiang, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">PHE, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">WHO, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">CDC, 2016a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">CDC, 2016b</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">Lalloo et al, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">PHE, 2016a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/malaria/references/\">WHO, 2016</a>]</p><!-- end field a66aa4fa-4201-48e0-aea1-2e7196733fe7 --><!-- end item 888b01af-4397-45c1-b74e-c173ab3d233a -->","topic":{"id":"a45cc869-8a29-5718-8d8c-fb4da11e3f58","topicId":"396f54ea-4a43-432a-964a-bf1c1d1ec304","topicName":"Malaria","slug":"malaria","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2017","chapters":[{"id":"77ca73e7-67fc-5532-afdd-8a33d4f624bc","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"1d13888f-5984-5ba7-b602-28290217579c","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"47353782-3c00-592f-bb46-5aed457f620b","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"c79fc9bf-9bf2-5be3-96a4-0e3a7b6c035d","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"170e13bf-3ada-54b4-b1da-bf3f2e576eff","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"edb18b0f-ecf6-511d-a62e-1a7193478cf6","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"e59bc905-80b7-59af-bcf3-18c542a8d661","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"016d9462-dbe7-5825-a4d6-41fc5e8d1de3","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"712ad264-c3b5-5462-be1e-e09e84881fdd","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"641a2f83-4b03-5455-8d1f-6d262c88ef45","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"beeed4d8-0061-5d53-9a52-4d9334fb0910","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"d4ec1d6f-3615-57b6-ae2a-adb55e52ea5d","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality standards"}]},{"id":"b057ab2c-b9ca-5c35-835c-b6eae8d2496a","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-informatio